sql:
SELECT MAX(win_count) AS max_win_count
FROM (
  SELECT winning_contestant_id, COUNT(*) AS win_count
  FROM episodes
  GROUP BY winning_contestant_id
);

SELECT COUNT(question_id)
FROM questions
WHERE question_text LIKE '%Galileo%';

external_knowledge:
- Total score is the sum of scores across all episodes for each contestant;
- The average score is the mean of all contestants' total scores;
- The number of episodes participated in is the count of unique episodes each contestant has been part of.

- 'Top performer' refers to the contestant with the highest score in each episode;
- The query ranks contestants by their scores within each episode;
- A contestant's performance is evaluated based on the score and the number of questions answered.

- "Star performer" refers to the winning contestant of the episode;
- "Curtain rose" refers to the air date of the episode;
- "Applause" refers to the score of the contestants.

- "shining star" metaphorically refers to the top-performing contestant;
- "clinched victory" means the contestant won their episodes;
- "outshone their peers" means the contestant scored higher than the average score in their episodes.

sql:
SELECT DISTINCT T1.name
FROM contestants T1
INNER JOIN episodes T3 ON T1.contestant_id = T3.winning_contestant_id;

SELECT episode_id, SUM(score) AS total_score
FROM contestant_episode
GROUP BY episode_id;

SELECT c.name, c.email
FROM contestants c
WHERE c.contestant_id IN (SELECT e.winning_contestant_id FROM episodes e);
